x4freetext: Experiment performed at the High
Intensity Gamma-Ray Source (HIGS) at Triangle
University Nuclear Laboratory in Durham
A 6Li target was built by casting
enriched 6Li inside a hollow teflon tube. The target
ends were capped using thin layers of polyvinyl
chloride and aluminum. Target diameter was 4.1 cm and
target length 12.7 cm was The thickness of the target
gave a good neutron production rate while causing
minimal time-of-flight resolution degradation.
Neutrons created by photodisintegration
reactions were detected using the Blowfish Neutron
Detector Array. Blowfish is a segmented fast neutron
detector based on 88 scintillating cells. It has a
radius of 40.6 cm and has an angular acceptance of
approximately 1/4 of 4Pi sr. The cells are filled
with the liquid scintillator BC505.
Nearly monochromatic polarized photon beam
produced by Compton backscattering of laser beam on
electrons, circulating in a synchrotron. The photon
beam is macroscopically continuous but photons arrive
in bunches 180 ns apart, since photons are scattered
on internal bunched electrons beam. Photon rates of
up to 10E+7 photons/s were used in these measurements.
Reaction channels were separated using fit of time of
flight spectra (tof) for individual channels to
experimental spectrum. Tof spectra for each reaction
channel was simulated using GEANT4 Monte Carlo code.
